Reply | Edit | Del All  a day of fishing<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Creapiing looked up from her desk as her assistant quietly walked in and dropped a new scroll upon the nearly finished work on her desk. Recognition crossed her face as she looked at the fresh seal upon the scroll. This information was something she had been waiting for all day. Cautiously, she removed the seal with her dagger and cast the red wax into the fire. Ominous crackling erupted and the smoke turned red and made a fiery dance upward.<br>
<br>
She eagerly read the contents of the scroll, and sweat beaded and dropped upon its words blurring them as she read. She reached for the pitcher of water on her desk only to find it empty for the second time this day. A racking cough hit her and she doubled over for a second, then straightened and motioned for her apprentice to fill the container.<br>
<br>
Payle had brought this terrible disease to Innoruuk’s chosen, but Mythral would be their salvation. The Mad One had forseen this in one of his alcoholic visions. Mythral’s release was the only way to know for sure the depth of the insanity caused by this dormant virus. This report would be the assessment of him, and would determine his ultimate fate. <br>
<br>
~we have followed Mythral noting his actions. He clearly has lost all mental facilities. He approaches every barbarian woman, calling them queen and shouts out that will rule Mistmoor. His wanderings seem to be random and not at all planned. Every short time he is forced to stop and find water, and he seems to be sweating in a most profuse manner. We await your orders.~<br>
<br>
Creapiing reached for parchment, and penned ~Take him now to the clerics in Neriak. He will be of no further use to us until after we explore the Crystal Caverns.~ She then removed a vial of dark red liquid and applied a seal to the scroll.<br>
<br>
She made a small motion, her apprentice scurried forward, snatched the scroll, and departed instantly.<br>
<br>
Creapiing looked about her office, her work for the day was done, stiffly she stood up, and walked over to her door, noting the blade of the silver shadows still stuck there. She reached for her fishing pole, ~it has been far too long~ she hurried to buy a few stacks of bait, and wished she had time to tie her own fishing flies. ~any chance to catch a few fish and break their necks is a good chance~ The Brightness of fires hurt her eyes and she clung to the shadows as she moved about the city. Down by the dock was a favorite spot where she could even catch fish with this inferior bait.. She reached the dock in record time and baited her pole and cast it out. <br>
<br>
Creapiing looked into the water, her fever burning bright, and dreamed of the coolness. ~woot! Fish on~ she pulled the flopping fish out and quickly broke its neck, watching its eyes glaze. The fish was so cool in her hand. Without a thought she pressed the cool body of the dead fish onto her burning forehead. ~ahhhhh! Much better.~<br>
<br>
Then she looked down and began to affix more bait to her line. As she did this, the dark shadowed water caught her eye. If the simple application of the fish brought her so much relief, how much more would come with immersion into the water. The deep dark color of the water seemed to call her as never before, the very ripples seemed to call her name. Creapiing stood, dropped her pole, and stripped off her armor. Looking at the depth of the water and the dark ripples upon it, she dove into the blackest part of the water.<br>
<br>
Instant relief filled her ravaged body. She swam down, into the darkness.<br>
<br>
Creapiing could not leave the water, she was driven in her delirium to stay in this place where she felt such relief. The last of her oxygen was gone and yet she could not make herself swim up to the surface where her gear lay. Slowly she drifting off into the dark comfort of the water, not caring if she lived or died, but focusing only upon the relief and pleasure the coolness and darkness brought to her.<br>
<br>
