Re: a day of fishing<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Khasirath sat back from his desk with a deep sigh of frustration. Dread Harvester Raveneye had presented the Triad with maps and scouting reports from the Crystal Caverns in preparation for their hunt, but the Thresher could not focus on the text. He wiped the sweat from his brow and poured himself another cup of the herbal tea that Vhalshae had brewed for his cough. Though it helped some, he could still feel the cursed illness ravaging his body, making every muscle ache and his head pound.<br>
<br>
He could not bear this waiting. He wanted to be off on the trail of the rogue Anari. The Winnower had heard her in Highpass - the blasted Fier'Dal had even dared to taunt her! Khasirath was ever more grateful for his talk with Creapiing, for it was now clear that Anari was trying to draw him out in a blind fury. Painful as it was he forced himself to wait. Soon the time described in the Scrolls would come, and the Harvest would be free of Bertoxxulous' Curse. Then he and the Reaper would find her.<br>
<br>
A wolfish grin spread over his dry cracked lips at the thought of facing Anari. He remembered well the sweet taste of her blood and her hate when he and Kvariya had broken her. Facing her in battle would be far more delicious. She had hatred now, and thought she could use it as a weapon against him. But he had learned much and grown stronger within the Harvest and Innoruuk's Will. He would show her how little she truly understood of hate, and we would enjoy it more deeply than what he had done to her in the Arena.<br>
<br>
Glancing back down at the reports, Khasirath let out a soft growl. This was simply not helping. He quickly finished the last of his tea and slung his baldric over his shoulder. As he stepped out of his office he fastened on his light cloak. Outside his door stood Alartha, one of his two personal servants. The young Teir'Dal warrioress awaited any command or need of her master, and bowed her head respectfully when he came into sight.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am going for a walk. If anyone needs me, get their name and tell them I should return in an hour.&quot; Alartha clasped her fist to her heart in salute, her sapphire eyes full of concern. She could see how the curse wore at her master's strength, and she knew she was powerless to stop it.<br>
<br>
As Khasirath walked the streets of Neriak, he wished he had brought a heavier cloak. Despite the fact that the air of Neriak was always warm due to its proximity to Lavastorm, the fever made the air seem chill, and his face grew clammy. He wandered a roundabout route through the Commons, thinking perhaps to stop at the Bleek Fletcher. His quiver had been growing light, and he would need to be well prepared for the coming hunts. He knew without having to look that Dythos, his other servant, would be nearby. The young rogue almost always shadowed his master's path through the city. 'A double-edged blade, such loyalty,' thought Khasirath. 'I can be secure of his presence, but not my own privacy.' A small smile passed over his face as he thought of those dark and impish eyes guarding his back.<br>
<br>
As Khasirath passed the gateway that led to the docks, something out of place caught his eye - a crumpled pile of dark armour near the water's edge. At first he thought it might be a fallen warrior, perhaps some lightborne who stumbled too far into the city. But the distinctive folds and patterns of the Darkforge armour was quickly apparent. With a rising feeling of dread, he quickened his pace towards the armour, crouching down for a better look. Darkforge it was, sized and molded for a female Teir'Dal. And then he saw it pinned to the cloak - the guildpin of the Reaper of the Harvest. His eyes grew wide as he stood, scanning the area for any sign of her. He noted the fishing pole and pots of bait at the edge of the dock, and the small carcass of some silvery fish. The boards of the docks were wet from a recent splash.<br>
<br>
&quot;Innoruuk, no!&quot; he mumbled in disbelief, frantically looking around. Trusting his instinct he flung off his cloak and dove into the deep water. His eyes were wide open he searched and searched, though his body soon began to shiver. The Thresher was a strong swimmer, having trained since he was young and Vlekk had demanded he go to the Ocean of Tears for siren scales. It was only the fact that swimming was so natural to him now that allowed him to continue, for his mind was too clouded by panic and illness to focus on such tasks. He circled around the pools and grottoes of stone, coming up for air only rarely, pushing his body beyond what he should.<br>
<br>
His ribs began to ache with the shivering, and the muscles were cramping in his legs as he rounded a boulder in the water. And there he found her floating face down, her white hair spread like a halo around her face. Gritting his teeth he swam to her side and rolled her over, supporting her carefully. Creapiing did not respond at all, and her eyes remained closed, but he could still feel the warmth of the fever burning beneath the clamminess of her soaked skin. Her brow sparkled where tiny silvery scales clung.<br>
<br>
Growling with the effort he lifted her waterlogged body onto the boulder and hoisted himself up beside her wild eyed. &quot;Reaper, can you hear me?&quot; he pleaded as he stroked her face, brushing her hair back.<br>
<br>
Did her eyes flutter a bit or was it his imagination? He could not tell if she was still breathing, and knew if she had no breath that his own powers could not revive her. The gifts of Innoruuk's Knights were only clumsily used for healing. He placed one hand over her chest, praying to feel it rise, but he felt nothing.<br>
<br>
&quot;Innoruuk, you can NOT let her die this way!&quot; he cried, shaking his head. He leaned down and turned her head a bit to meet his own as he pressed his lips to hers, trying to breathe his life into her, pleading within himself for her to take his life, to live. Again and again he breathed into her, and suddenly she began to cough, water pouring up from her lungs. Khasirath rolled her to her side, helping support her as the spasms wracked her body. He drew on his hate and the Father's gift and poured his life-force into her, feeling himself shivering as violently as she was. The water danced and the cavern walls seemed to undulate around them, the darkness pressing in. Creapiing clutched at his arms as she tried to sit up, breathing in ragged gulps. Khasirath clung to her tightly as he knelt on the stone, his head pounding with the pain and weakness of giving his life to her. He feared he might not be able to stand at all.<br>
<br>
<br>
