Re: a day of fishing<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Vresk sat in the middle of the room, thick incense smoke filling his nostrils and expanding his mind. He felt a wave of calm and peace surround him. For a tidy sum, he had “permanently” rented this room in the middle of Neriak Commons. His home away from home.<br>
<br>
Though Vresk was highly adaptable, and had earned the respect of many in the Violent Harvest, the ways of the Softskins still bewildered him at times. It was pleasant for him to have this little piece of Kunark where he could find sanctuary from culture shock.<br>
<br>
As his meditation deepened, the monk’s mind slipped into a higher consciousness. Instinctively, his throat began to hum and chant in the ancient tongue of his people<br>
<br>
After several minutes his body relaxed even further, and the clouds in his mind separated. Images began to form, his inner consciousness providing him with the enlightenment he sought. Several minutes passed, with the monk not moving even to breathe.<br>
<br>
Suddenly the images stopped, and Vresk’s mind’s eye focused in on the picture before him. He saw two figures sprawled out on a rock near a body of water. Their limbs were akimbo, as if a child had thrown two dolls to the ground and this was how they lay. A red haze descended over the image, a sign of imminent danger. A sickly green aura surrounded the two, and Vresk recognized this as illness. And then the images were gone.<br>
<br>
The monk stood, jolted out of his deep meditation. His conscious mind recognized the rock as being very near his location in Neriak, by the border of the neighborhood known as the Foreign Quarter. Alarmed, but calm, Vresk knew that only an emergency to those he served could have pried him from his meditations.<br>
<br>
He grabbed his change purse and swiftly glided downstairs.<br>
<br>
---------------------------<br>
<br>
Once at the ground level, he located the barkeep wiping tables, preparing for the evening’s business. The Iksar approached from behind, waiting to be recognized. After 15 seconds, Vresk cleared his throat loudly, the urgency of his situation driving him to impatience.<br>
<br>
The barkeep nearly fell over at the sound, not having heard the monk’s soft footsteps. He did fall over completely when he saw the Iksar’s grisly image. “Oh deark Innoruuk!” he cried as he fell.<br>
<br>
Vresk, feeling bad for the old Teir’Dal, bent to help him up, but the man scrambled away from the ulcerous hand in alarm. “Whoah now! It’s okay,” he said, getting back to his feet. After a few moments of breathing deeply and repeating “I’m okay,” he finally settled a look on the Iksar.<br>
<br>
“Now listen here, ya scaly lizard!” he bellowed. “Ya can’t just go bargin up ta folks like that! Learn to make some noise or something, so people can hear ya comin’. Scared me half ta death ya did!”<br>
<br>
Vresk’s tail twitched in irritation. Here was a prime example of the Softskin’s confusing ways. The man was clearly upset because Vresk had approached unheard. Yet he was being chastised for “barging,” which the Iksar had learned was a way of saying that one was being obnoxiously noisy and rude. Besides, wasn’t it a Teir’Dal saying that the best knife was the one behind the back? Or was it the unseen dagger…? Vresk shook his head, trying to clear it of extraneous thought. He didn’t have time for this.<br>
<br>
“Forgive the intrusion on your work,” he said, bowing low. “But I have ssome tasskss that you will complete now.”<br>
<br>
The Teir’Dal looked at him half with rage at the audacity of the foreigner telling him what to do and half with pity at the obviously advanced stage the disease had eaten away at his body. “Now look here ya bleedin’ puss-ridden snake,” Vresk ignored the insult. He was used to being referred to as “snake” or “lizard” by this man, it seemed to be terms of affection almost. As far as the bleeding and the puss-ridden statement, both were true, so he saw no reason to be upset. “I have a thousand things to get ready for tonight’s business…”<br>
<br>
The barkeep trailed off as Vresk tossed a pouch at him. It jingled very satisfactorily in the hand. Frowning a bit at the weight, he untied the silk string tying it together and poured several coins into his hand. He gasped when he saw the number. “By Innoruuk man! There must be over 50 imperial platinum in this bag!”<br>
<br>
“One hundred to be preccisse,” Vresk hissed.<br>
<br>
The man blinked at the number. This was almost a week’s worth of business. “What do you need done?” he asked, making the pouch disappear.<br>
<br>
“Honorable Inkeeper, I require you to get together four pitcherss of your coldesst water. Thesse are to be sset in the room nexst to mine. Alsso in that room, you will take two wash bassinss, your finesst mind you, not the ssubsstandard fair you provide for foreigners like me, and fill them halfway with icce. Then you are to fill them the resst of the way with cool water. Are thesse insstructionss clear sso far? They musst be exsact.” The man nodded solemnly, too shocked to notice the comment about the quality of his services to the monk. “Good,” he said, pulling several vials from another pouch. “You will give thesse to your cook. I require two mealss prepared. Make it your finesst meat. Alsso, have the cook pour thesse vialss into 2 gobletss of goat’ss milk.”<br>
<br>
“What are these?” the inkeeper asked.<br>
<br>
“Ssarnak blood.”<br>
<br>
The inkeeper nodded solemnly, then narrowed his eyes in suspicion. “Ye ain’t plannin’ on bringin’ any more of yer kind here are ya?”<br>
<br>
“No.”<br>
<br>
“Good, cuz one of ya around is bad enough. What, with yer bleedin’ all over and such. If not onna yer kind, then who?”<br>
<br>
“A pair of Teir’Dal nobless shall temporarily gracce thesse hallss. Pleasse, for your life, make sure you follow my insstructionss exsactly. Failure to do sso may ressult in their death. I do not believe THAT would be good for bussinesss at all.” With that, the Iksar ghosted out the door.<br>
<br>
------------------<br>
<br>
Vresk dove into the cool waters of Neriak Commons. Like all Iksar, his body was built specifically for swimming, and he slid as easily through the lake as he would on land. The monk revelled in the cool feeling of the water against the many sores and postules infesting his scales. While the Teir’Dal were affected by terrible fever and cough, he had been affected by a terrible wasting. From his recent bowel movements, his insides didn’t look much better than his outside.<br>
<br>
Within moments he arrived at the spot his meditations had led him to. Sure enough, laying there, gasping against each other, the Ambassador to Kunark found both the Reaper and Thresher wrapped around each other. Off to one side, Vresk noted another he did not recognize. He hovered nearby, but did not seem to be a threat.<br>
<br>
As he approached, he heard the Reaper whisper, “You smell like fish.”<br>
<br>
“Ssome would ssay I am a fish, Reaper,” he whispered back.<br>
<br>
He knelt beside the Thresher, knowing he had magics that would assist the three of them in getting back safely to the inn he had prepared. “Thresher,” he said as he nudged the shadowknight.<br>
<br>
“Hunh…” Khasirath responded.<br>
<br>
“Thresher Khassirath, Lord Innoruuk hass ssent me to retrieve you. You are to drain my sstrength for your own.”<br>
<br>
This seemed to trigger something within the Teir’Dal. Steeling himself, he managed to mutter the proper incantation. There was a small thunderclap, and both Khasirath and Vresk were surrounded with a red aura. The Iksar felt a small portion of his strength drain.<br>
<br>
Khasirath stood up, a grim, pained look on his face. “Ambassador, you look like Hell,” he said.<br>
<br>
“I imagine I do, Thresher. Though I have come for you nonethelesss. It iss not ssafe for the two of you to appear to your people in thiss sstate. If you will help me carry the Reaper, I have made reparationss for the two of you.”<br>
<br>
He turned to the one he did not recognize. “Will you help uss?” he asked simply.<br>
<br>
