Re: a day of fishing<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Panting raggedly, Khasirath clung to both the rock and the Reaper, listening to the soft chattering of his own teeth as he inwardly cursed his impulsiveness. He had Creapiing, she was safe at the moment, but he had no way to get them back to the docks and ensure their safety.<br>
<br>
Suddenly Khasirath heard an unfamiliar voice from behind, &quot;Dark Knight of the Father, I know naught what has befallen your ally of the Harvest, but I would be honored to assist. You have it right I believe, it is not the healing magics of a Priest that is needed but the maledict force of the Dead.&quot; <br>
<br>
Khasirath turned his head unsteadily and looked up at the dark figure, most likely a noble like himself by the style of his garb and hair. The Thresher did not recognize the man, though there was something familiar about the angles of his face ... perhaps he was related to someone Khasirath did know. As he watched, the unknown Knight pulled on his gloves and knelt nearer to the Reaper.<br>
<br>
&quot;Let me aid thee, Brother. We will take her to the Masters of the Lodge. The unhallowed grace of the Father will awaken this fierce Knight, as she ought to be....&quot; <br>
<br>
Khasirath frowned, marshaling his own failing strength. &quot;I do appreciate your concern, Brother of the Dead, but the Lodge cannot help her, or me. Neither can the Spires. Only we of the Harvest can cure ourselves, but we must survive long enough to do so.&quot;<br>
<br>
As he spoke, the Reapers stirred for a moment, and he just barely heard her whisper, &quot;You smell like fish.&quot;<br>
<br>
Immense relief surged through him at hearing her voice, weak though it was, and a small smile spread over his face at the absurdity of what she'd said. <br>
<br>
Just then Khasirath felt a nudge, and a familiar sibilant voice said, &quot;Thresher.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Hunh...&quot; he blurted, caught off guard as he had been so focused on the Knight and the Reaper that he had not heard the Iksar's silent approach. He shook his head in annoyance with himself for being so careless.<br>
<br>
“Thresher Khassirath, Lord Innoruuk hass ssent me to retrieve you. You are to drain my sstrength for your own.”<br>
<br>
Khasirath turned to look at the Ambassador more fully, seeing how the patches of pustules were spreading over the Monk's scaled flesh. Indeed he must be in great pain from it all, but he bore it silently, and had even come to help. Reaching deep to connect with his hatred, Khasirath whispered the incantations, and drew the Iksar's lifeforce into himself. He let out a hissing breath as he was almost overcome by the pleasure that always brought him, and the alien yet familiar 'taste' of the Iksar's life.<br>
<br>
Khasirath stood slowly as he looked Vresk over, hoping he had not weakened him too much. “Ambassador, you look like Hell,” he said.<br>
<br>
“I imagine I do, Thresher. Though I have come for you nonethelesss. It iss not ssafe for the two of you to appear to your people in thiss sstate. If you will help me carry the Reaper, I have made reparationss for the two of you.”<br>
<br>
Vresk turned towards the other Knight. “Will you help uss?”<br>
<br>
Khasirath looked back to the Knight with a nod, &quot;Your help would be greatly appreciated.&quot;<br>
