Silently Dythos waited in the shadows on the docks, his heart hammering. His master had been gone for far too long. He crept to the edge of the water, near the pile of armour that had caused Khasirath to go rushing off looking for the Reaper. Dythos knew who she was, as he sometimes acted as Khasirath's scribe during meetings. He had a distinct feeling the Reaper disliked him immediately, so he tried to stay out of her way whenever possible.<br>
<br>
As a servant, Dythos knew plenty about staying out of the way, and also of staying unseen. From a very young age, he and Alartha had served Khasirath, and had been well trained by House S`Therik on how it was to be done. Both of them had grown very close to their master, who had always treated them well. In his heart, Dythos knew he would die for Khasirath if it was what his master asked or needed. There was simply no questioning his loyalty.<br>
<br>
But this? How best to help Khasirath? Dythos was not that good in the water, and did not know the pools and grottoes of Neriak like Khasirath did. The bathing pools of House S`Therik were as much swimming as he could handle. He probably wouldn't be able to find Khasirath or Creapiing. And the Reaper's armour! Dythos knew how valuable it was, and that it wouldn't be able to sit on the docks for long before someone would help themselves to the treasure. Khasirath had been unwell for some time, and Dythos was not sure he would be able to swim for this long. He couldn't just take the armour back to the House without knowing his master was alright.<br>
<br>
So the young rogue stood on the docks, trying to stay in the shadows, taking a step closer to the water than a step towards the armour and back in his indecision. He kept glancing back through the archway to the street, hoping someone he recignized as an ally of the House or the Harvest might walk by, so he could beg for their aid. And he also wanted to be on guard lest someone notice the Darkforge sitting unattended.  <br>
